@@eThe Great Northern Forest@@N

Four hundred square miles of unbroken canopy stretch between
@@yMidgaard@@N to the south and @@yKowloon@@N to the north. This is no
mere wilderness -- it is a @@gnegotiated artery@@N, governed jointly by
both cities under a compact older than most living institutions.

The @@yLantern Road@@N winds through the forest along game trails and
dry streambeds, bending where the land demands. Its architect, Ilren
Voss, followed a doctrine called the @@WBent Mile Principle@@N: the
wiser road is the one that bends around flood, den, and sacred grove.
Lantern posts mark each ford and turn in both Midgaard runes and
northern knot-signs.

The @@WNorthern Covenant@@N, signed at a neutral glade called the
Oath-Crossing, forbids armies from marching the road in war formation,
restricts timbering to safety cuts, and declares shrine groves
inviolable. Neither city claims the forest as sole territory.

Two centuries ago, three successive @@rAsh Winters@@N -- volcanic fallout
from the distant Cinderteeth -- poisoned streams and killed a third
of the large game. Hunger turned territorial disputes into ambush wars
and forged the first @@yPassage Tithe@@N system, where caravans paid in
grain, salt, lamp oil, and iron nails rather than coin alone.

The forest is home to many peoples. @@gRoadwardens@@N and lamp-keepers
maintain waystones along the route. @@dMire-clans@@N in fen basins trade
resin, fish oil, and medicinal bark from woven reed platforms.
@@WStone-antler circles@@N guard megalith rings older than either city,
forbidding entry without ritual permission. @@rAshfang warbands@@N --
exiles who blacken their teeth with ash -- raid road traffic and sell
intelligence to whichever city will pay.

Five ecological zones ring the road in ascending danger: the sunlit
@@gSouthern Verge@@N, the treacherous @@lMosswater Bends@@N, the dense
@@dIronpine Rise@@N, the ancient @@eAncestor Deeps@@N where luminescent
moss carpets the ground, and the cold @@WNorthern Crown@@N where Kowloon's
Wardens of Iron conduct clearing patrols.

Recurring omens mark the forest's moods: the @@ylantern-and-scale@@N
motif carved on waystones, the @@gsplit pine@@N of adaptation on bridge
keystones, the @@Wwhite stag@@N that appears before faction war, and
the @@rred moss bloom@@N that warns of corrupted groves.
